<article title='Transport_in_Brazil'><paragraph><template><target>Cleanup</target><arg name="date">December 2012<space/></arg><arg name="reason">Unchecked vandalism may have compromised this article â€“ need to check the statements and links to verify that they're not bogus.</arg></template><bold>Transport infrastructure</bold><space/>in<space/><link><target>Brazil</target></link><space/>is characterized by strong regional differences and lack of development of the national rail network.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.dhl-discoverlogistics.com/cms/en/course/trends/america/brazil.jsp'>Logistics in Brazil - DHL Logistik</link></extension><space/>Brazil's fast-growing economy, and especially the growth in exports, will place increasing demands on the transport networks.<extension extension_name='ref' name="ic.gc.ca">http://www.ic.gc.ca/scdt/bizmap/interface2.nsf/vDownload/ISA_3976/$file/X_9317614.PDF</extension><space/>However, sizeable new investments that are expected to address some of the issues are either planned or in progress.<extension extension_name='ref' name="ic.gc.ca"></extension><extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.bsdlive.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=3130466'>Home page | The world's leading construction web site</link></extension></paragraph><heading level='2'><link><target>Rail transport</target><part>Railways</part></link></heading><paragraph><link><target>Image:Rodovia dos Imigrantes 1.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part><link><target>Rodovia dos Imigrantes</target></link></part></link><template><target>Main</target><arg>Rail transport in Brazil</arg></template><template><target>Further</target><arg>RFFSA</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><bold>Total actual network:</bold><space/>29,303&amp;nbsp;km</listitem></list><list type='ident'><listitem><link><target>Broad gauge</target></link>: 4,932 km<space/><template><target>RailGauge</target><arg>1.6m</arg></template><space/>gauge (939 km electrified)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Narrow gauge railway</target><part>Narrow gauge</part></link>: 23,773 km<space/><template><target>RailGauge</target><arg>1000mm</arg></template><space/>gauge (581 km electrified)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Dual gauge</target></link>: 396 km 1000 mm and 1600 mm gauges (three rails)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Standard gauge</target></link>: 202.4 km<space/><template><target>RailGauge</target><arg>sg</arg></template><space/>gauge: (2006)</listitem></list><preblock><preline>*<space/><link><target>Amapa Railway</target><part>Estrada de Ferro do Amap</part></link><space/>in the middle of the<space/><link><target>Amazon Rainforest</target></link><space/>also used standard gauge.</preline></preblock><list type='bullet'><listitem>A 12&amp;nbsp;km section of the former<space/><template><target>RailGauge</target><arg>2ft6in</arg></template><space/>gauge<space/><link><target>Estrada de Ferro Oeste de Minas</target></link><space/>is retained as a<space/><link><target>heritage railway</target></link>.</listitem></list><heading level='3'>Cities with Metros</heading><paragraph><link><target>Image:TUE TRENSURB 113.JPG</target><part>thumb</part><part><link><target>Porto Alegre Metro</target></link></part></link></paragraph><table><tablerow valign="top"><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Belo Horizonte</target></link><space/>(28,2 km)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Braslia Metro</target><part>Braslia</part></link><space/>(42,4 km)<space/></listitem><listitem><link><target>Fortaleza</target></link><space/>(24,1 km)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Porto Alegre</target></link><space/>(43,4 km)<space/></listitem><listitem><link><target>Sobral</target></link><space/>(11,0 km)</listitem></list></tablecell><tablecell width="40"></tablecell><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Juazeiro do Norte</target></link><space/>(13,9 km)<space/></listitem><listitem><link><target>Recife</target></link><space/>(71 km)<space/></listitem><listitem><link><target>Rio de Janeiro Metro</target><part>Rio de Janeiro</part></link><space/>(40,9 km)</listitem><listitem><link><target>So Paulo Metro</target><part>So Paulo</part></link><space/>(75,5 km)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Salvador, Bahia</target><part>Salvador</part></link><space/>(7,3 km)</listitem><listitem><link><target>Teresina</target></link><space/>(13,5 km)</listitem></list></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='3'>Railway links with adjacent countries</heading><paragraph><template><target>Main</target><arg>Rail transport in Brazil#Railway links with adjacent countries</arg></template>International rail links exist between Brazil and<space/><link><target>Transport in Argentina</target><part>Argentina</part></link>,<space/><link><target>Transport in Bolivia</target><part>Bolivia</part></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Transport in Uruguay</target><part>Uruguay</part></link>.</paragraph><heading level='3'><link><target>Tram</target><trail>ways</trail></link><space/>(Street Railways)</heading><paragraph>Brazil had a hundred tramway systems.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/tto/1.html'>Introduction</link></extension><space/>Currently, there are vintage tramways operating in Belm,<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/be/be50.html'>The Tramways of Belm</link></extension><space/>Campinas,<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/cp/pp.html'>The Tramways of Campinas</link></extension><space/>Campos do Jordo,<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/cj/cj.html'>Campos do Jordo</link></extension><space/>Itatinga,<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/it/it.html'>CODESP hydroelectric complex (Brazil)</link></extension><space/>Rio de Janeiro<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/rj/st/st.html'>The Santa Teresa Tramway</link></extension><space/>and Santos.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.tramz.com/br/ss/st.html'>The Scottish Trams Of Santos</link></extension></paragraph><heading level='3'>High-speed rail</heading><paragraph><template><target>Main</target><arg>High-speed rail in Brazil</arg></template>A<space/><link><target>high-speed rail</target></link><space/>connecting<space/><link><target>So Paulo</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>Rio de Janeiro</target></link><space/>is currently under development.<extension extension_name='ref'><link type='external' href='http://www.rio2016.org.br/en/Noticias/Noticia.aspx?idConteudo=492'>In Tokyo Rio governor assures high speed rail</link><space/><link><target>Rio 2016</target></link>. Retrieved on 2009-06-21.</extension></paragraph><heading level='2'><link><target>Highway</target><trail>s</trail></link></heading><paragraph><italics><template><target>Main</target><arg>Brazilian Highway System</arg></template></italics>Brazil has 1,751,868 kilometers of roads, 96,353&amp;nbsp;km of them paved and 1,655,515&amp;nbsp;km unpaved. That means that only 5.5% of the roads are paved and that 94.5% are unpaved. The most important highway of the country is<space/><link><target>BR-116</target></link><space/>and the second is<space/><link><target>BR-101</target></link>.</paragraph><paragraph>The country has a low rate of car ownership of 140 per 1000 population, however in comparison to the other developing economies of the<space/><link><target>BRIC</target></link><space/>group Brazil exceeds India and China.</paragraph><heading level='2'><link><target>Waterway</target><trail>s</trail></link></heading><paragraph>50,000&amp;nbsp;km<space/><link><target>navigable</target></link><space/>(most in areas remote from industry or population) (2008)</paragraph><heading level='2'><link><target>Pipeline transport</target><part>Pipelines</part></link></heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Natural-gas condensate</target><part>condensate</part></link>/gas 62&amp;nbsp;km</listitem><listitem><link><target>natural gas</target></link><space/>9,892&amp;nbsp;km</listitem><listitem><link><target>liquid petroleum</target></link><space/>gas 353&amp;nbsp;km</listitem><listitem><link><target>crude oil</target></link><space/>4,517&amp;nbsp;km</listitem><listitem>refined products 4,465&amp;nbsp;km (2008)</listitem></list><heading level='2'><link><target>Seaports</target></link><space/>and<space/><link><target>harbor</target><trail>s</trail></link></heading><heading level='3'>Atlantic Ocean</heading><paragraph><link><target>Image:JaceguaiNatal2009.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part><link><target>Port of Natal</target></link></part></link></paragraph><table><tablerow valign="top"><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Fortaleza</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Ilheus</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Imbituba</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Paranagu</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Porto Alegre</target></link></listitem></list></tablecell><tablecell width="40"></tablecell><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Recife</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Rio de Janeiro</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Rio Grande, Rio Grande do Sul</target><part>Rio Grande</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Salvador, Brazil</target><part>Salvador</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Santos (So Paulo)</target><part>Santos</part></link></listitem></list></tablecell><tablecell width="40"></tablecell><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>So Francisco do Sul</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>So Sebastio, So Paulo</target><part>So Sebastio</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Vitria, Brazil</target><part>ES</part></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Itaja</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Natal, Brazil</target><part>Natal</part></link></listitem></list></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='3'><link><target>Amazon river</target></link></heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Belm</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Manaus</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='3'><link><target>Paraguay River</target></link><space/>(<link><target>International waters</target><part>international water way</part></link>)</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Corumb</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'><link><target>Merchant marine</target></link></heading><paragraph><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>total:</italics>136 ships (<template><target>GRT</target><arg>1,000</arg><arg name="disp">long</arg></template><space/>or over) totaling<space/><template><target>GRT</target><arg>3,964,808</arg></template>/<template><target>DWT</target><arg>6,403,284</arg><arg>metric</arg><arg name="disp">long</arg></template><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>ships by type:</italics><space/>(1999 est.)</paragraph><table><tablerow valign="top"><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>bulk carrier</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>19</listitem><listitem><link><target>cargo ship</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>22</listitem><listitem><link><target>carrier ship</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>1</listitem><listitem><link><target>chemical tanker</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>7</listitem><listitem><link><target>container ship</target><trail>s</trail></link><space/>11</listitem><listitem><link><target>LNG carrier</target><part>gas carrying tankers</part></link><space/>12</listitem></list></tablecell><tablecell width="40"></tablecell><tablecell><list type='bullet'><listitem>multi-functional large load carrier 1</listitem><listitem><link><target>Passenger ship</target><part>passenger/cargo ships</part></link><space/>12</listitem><listitem><link><target>petroleum tanker</target></link><space/>45</listitem><listitem><link><target>roll-on/roll-off</target></link><space/>7</listitem></list></tablecell></tablerow></table><heading level='2'>Airports</heading><paragraph><template><target>see also</target><arg>List of airports in Brazil</arg></template><link><target>File:ViewfromAir-SaoPaulo.jpg</target><part>thumb</part><part><link><target>So PauloGuarulhos International Airport</target></link>.</part></link><link><target>File:Rio de Janeiro-Galeo International Airport.December.01.2011.JPG</target><part>thumb</part><part><link><target>Rio de Janeiro-Galeo International Airport</target></link>.</part></link>Most international flights must go to<space/><link><target>So PauloGuarulhos International Airport</target></link><space/>or<space/><link><target>Rio de JaneiroGaleo International Airport</target></link>. Belo Horizonte is the main international airport outside Rio de Janeiro and So Paulo. A few go to Braslia, Recife, Natal, and just recently Fortaleza has accepted international flights. With South American integration, more airports can be expected to open to international flights.</paragraph><paragraph>In 2013 Brazil had the sixth largest passenger air market in the world.<extension extension_name='ref'>World Bank Datebase, http://data.worldbank.org/indicator/IS.AIR.PSGR</extension></paragraph><heading level='3'>Airports - with paved runways</heading><paragraph><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>total:</italics>734<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>over 3,047 m:</italics>7<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>2,438 to 3,047 m:</italics>26<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>1,524 to 2,437 m:</italics>169<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>914 to 1,523 m:</italics>476<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>under 914 m:</italics>56 (2008)</paragraph><heading level='3'>Airports - with unpaved runways</heading><paragraph><xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>total:</italics>3,442<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>1,524 to 2,437 m:</italics>85<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>914 to 1,523 m:</italics>1,541<xhtml:br></xhtml:br><italics>under 914 m:</italics>1,816 (2008)</paragraph><heading level='2'>National<space/><link><target>airline</target><trail>s</trail></link></heading><paragraph><template><target>Main</target><arg>List of airlines of Brazil</arg></template></paragraph><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Azul Linhas Areas Brasileiras</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Gol Transportes Areos</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>Avianca</target></link></listitem><listitem><link><target>TAM Airlines</target></link><space/>(TAM Linhas Areas)</listitem></list><heading level='2'>Heliports</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem>16 (2007)</listitem><listitem>13 (2010)</listitem></list><heading level='2'>See also</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link><target>Rail transport by country</target></link></listitem></list><heading level='2'>References</heading><list type='bullet'><listitem><link type='external' href='https://www.cia.gov/library/publications/the-world-factbook/geos/br.html'>CIA - The World Factbook - Brazil - Transportation</link></listitem></list><paragraph><template><target>reflist</target><arg>2</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>Airlines of Brazil</target></template><template><target>Economy of Brazil</target></template><template><target>Brazil topics</target></template><template><target>Americas topic</target><arg>Transport in</arg></template></paragraph><paragraph><template><target>DEFAULTSORT:Transport In Brazil</target></template><link><target>Category:Transport in Brazil</target><part></part></link></paragraph></article>